@dabeaz: I think it's intended to fix the oddities discussed in #112, not #106. Also it's a precondition to fancier scheduling policies, like discussed in #91 and #114. I guess it also makes the current scheduling algorithm into a stricter variant of FIFO, for whatever that's worth.

I think the only connection to #106 would be that this enables fancier scheduling policies, and if we had a fancier scheduling policy (e.g. one that explicitly reasons about fairness), and it was efficient enough, then we could potentially have a schedule point inside `Socket.recv`/`Socket.sendall`, but still kind-of preserve eager-read/write in the sense that we would only *actually* schedule away in read/write if scheduler determined that the task was hogging the CPU.

The I/O-polling thread I suggested in [this comment](https://github.com/dabeaz/curio/issues/106#issuecomment-260232149) was me trying to think of ways to get the semantics of this PR but while keeping the per-schedule overhead as low as possible.

